 prism of gender studies and by stressing questions of femininity, motherhood and sexuality, the subject appears in a new light. This research highlights the importance of intertwining Jewish literary study with comparative religion and gender theories, enabling the process of filling in the ‘mythic gaps’ in classical Jewish sources. The book won the Pines, Lakritz and Warburg awards.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aJewish mythology. 0aMessiahxJudaism. 0aMothers and sonsxReligious aspectsxJudaism. 0aMothers in the Bible. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Jewish Studies.2bisacsh1 aMatanky, Eugene D.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertReligious Studies ASPz978311071683240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978161811561440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781618115614423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781618115614.jpg  a978-3-11-071683-2  Religious Studies ASP  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK